                                                        <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>3</watches>
                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="139217" author="kaiming" created="Tue, 19 Jan 2016 05:11:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;No, MDT can&apos;t be mounted. I have mounted MGT and MDT before OST but it still has the same problem. Now, I found maybe it is a software bug, because I change it into Lustre2.7.0 and it works well. Thank you for your help!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="139216" author="malkolm" created="Tue, 19 Jan 2016 04:25:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Do the mount or df commands show the MDT as mounted? If so, this error can be ignored, I think, as a side-effect of not having any OSTs connected to the file system. For first time mounts, you have to mount the MGT and MDTs before the OSTs, but you get this side-effect.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="138697" author="adilger" created="Tue, 12 Jan 2016 18:20:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Also, you need at least one OST mounted for the filesystem to be useful. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="138696" author="adilger" created="Tue, 12 Jan 2016 18:19:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Did you check for errors on the console (demagogue)? This is typically caused by problems with host name resolution (e.g. host name maps to local host in /etc/hosts) or firewall rules that prevent connection on port 988. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
